00:11:41.629 --> 00:11:42.298
Right?
 

00:11:42.298 --> 00:11:45.855
The area of the loop which
points perpendicular to that has

00:11:45.855 --> 00:11:48.918
a value equal to l
times w.

00:11:48.918 --> 00:11:50.740
so l times
w is area,

00:11:50.740 --> 00:11:53.408
so I times area is
called the magnetic moment,

00:11:53.408 --> 00:12:00.275
and that times B times
sinθ is the cross

00:12:00.275 --> 00:12:01.440
product.
 

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:06.684
So what you notice is that the
torque will turn it till

00:12:06.684 --> 00:12:09.600
μ x B is 0.
 

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:12.349
That will occur when
μ and B are

00:12:12.349 --> 00:12:14.009
parallel, or anti-parallel.
 

00:12:14.009 --> 00:12:15.798
There are the only two options.
 

00:12:15.798 --> 00:12:18.077
When they are the parallel,
the area vector's along

00:12:18.077 --> 00:12:18.580
B.
 

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:21.456
When they're anti-parallel,
the area vector's exactly

00:12:21.456 --> 00:12:22.730
opposite to B.
 

00:12:22.730 --> 00:12:26.320
And they are the two
equilibrium positions.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:28.509
But one is the point of maximum
energy;

00:12:28.509 --> 00:12:32.100
one is the point of minimum
energy, just like with the

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:33.320
electric dipole.
 

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:37.494
Once you have a torque like
this, you can find the potential

00:12:37.494 --> 00:12:41.101
energy and you can show the
potential energy is just

00:12:41.101 --> 00:12:45.011
-μBcosθ,
which is

00:12:45.011 --> 00:12:49.779
