00:30:07.009 --> 00:30:09.828
And by symmetry,
they will have the same angle,

00:30:09.828 --> 00:30:12.709
so you only have to keep the
z component,

00:30:12.709 --> 00:30:15.098
not the one in the xy
plane.

00:30:15.098 --> 00:30:18.278
Because for every element I
find here, I can find a

00:30:18.278 --> 00:30:21.519
compensating one on the other
side of the circle.

00:30:21.519 --> 00:30:26.170
So therefore,
dB along the z

00:30:26.170 --> 00:30:30.143
direction is
μ_0I/

00:30:30.143 --> 00:30:36.282
4Π times the
segment coming out of the

00:30:36.282 --> 00:30:38.210
blackboard.
 

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:39.368
What about the
sinθ?

00:30:39.368 --> 00:30:42.029
Sine theta, here's where you've
got to be very careful.

00:30:42.029 --> 00:30:48.884
What do you think the
sinθ is between the

00:30:48.884 --> 00:30:55.608
segment coming out of the
blackboard and this guy?

00:30:55.608 --> 00:30:58.096
What's the angle between a line
that lies in the plane of the

00:30:58.096 --> 00:31:00.420
blackboard, and the line coming
out of the blackboard?

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:02.089
Student:  Ninety.
 

00:31:02.089 --> 00:31:02.769
Prof: Ninety.
 

00:31:02.769 --> 00:31:04.700
Don't be fooled by anything
else.

00:31:04.700 --> 00:31:07.365
Anything coming out of the
blackboard is orthogonal to

00:31:07.365 --> 00:31:09.480
anything in the plane of the
blackboard.

00:31:09.480 --> 00:31:11.821
The wire is coming out of the
blackboard, this vector's in the

00:31:11.821 --> 00:31:12.130
plane.
 

00:31:12.130 --> 00:31:14.950
There's no sine thetas to worry
about.

00:31:14.950 --> 00:31:19.346
But you've got to divide by the
square of the distance,

00:31:19.346 --> 00:31:23.579
and the square of the distance
happens to be z^(2)

00:31:23.579 --> 00:31:24.720
R^(2).
 

00:31:24.720 --> 00:31:26.640
That's the square of the
distance.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:31.940
That will give you this part,
but I want that part.

00:31:31.940 --> 00:31:35.358
So that's cosine of this angle
α.

00:31:35.358 --> 00:31:38.440
Now let's see where I can get
the same cosine.

00:31:38.440 --> 00:31:42.109
The angle between two lines is
the same as the angle between

00:31:42.109 --> 00:31:45.221
the perpendiculars,
so that guy is perpendicular to

00:31:45.221 --> 00:31:46.029
this guy.
 

00:31:46.029 --> 00:31:49.465
This guy is perpendicular to
that guy, so that will also be

00:31:49.465 --> 00:31:49.940
alpha.
 

00:31:49.940 --> 00:32:01.464
And cosine α
will be R divided by z^(2)

00:32:01.464 --> 00:32:06.858
R^(2), ½.
 

00:32:06.858 --> 00:32:08.920
So the sinθ didn't
come because of a

00:32:08.920 --> 00:32:10.680
sinθ in the cross
product.

00:32:10.680 --> 00:32:13.955
This factor,
it came because you want the

00:32:13.955 --> 00:32:17.970
projection of this vector up the
z axis.

00:32:17.970 --> 00:32:19.978
We are not done,
because this is a contribution

00:32:19.978 --> 00:32:22.250
from a tiny link dl coming out
of the blackboard,

00:32:22.250 --> 00:32:25.382
but notice the contribution is
independent of where you are on

00:32:25.382 --> 00:32:26.048
the circle.
 

00:32:26.048 --> 00:32:29.220
Everything makes a contribution
up the z axis.

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:32.213
Each one makes a contribution
dl, so if you add up all

00:32:32.213 --> 00:32:34.509
of these, there's nothing to
integrate here.

00:32:34.509 --> 00:32:35.750
That's what I want you to
notice.

00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:37.160
z and R are fixed.
 

00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:40.654
You've just got to integrate
dl, which will be

00:32:40.654 --> 00:32:41.730
2ΠR.
 

00:32:41.730 --> 00:32:47.338
So I get μ_0
I/2ΠR squared,

00:32:47.338 --> 00:32:57.700
divided by 4Π,
divided by z^(2) R^(2)

00:32:57.700 --> 00:33:01.980
to the power 3/2.
 

00:33:01.980 --> 00:33:05.740
That is the magnetic field here.
 

00:33:05.740 --> 00:33:12.880
So along the axis,
it will go like this.

00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:17.358
And what is it at the center of
the loop?

00:33:17.358 --> 00:33:18.838
That's a useful formula to
remember.

00:33:18.838 --> 00:33:23.538
At the center,
you put z = 0,

00:33:23.538 --> 00:33:26.964
you get
μ_0I times

00:33:26.964 --> 00:33:33.288
2ΠR^(2),
divided by 4ΠR^(3).

00:33:33.288 --> 00:33:41.973
That gives me
μ_0I/2R

00:33:41.973 --> 00:33:44.868
Tesla.
 

00:33:44.868 --> 00:33:47.358
And it's going to be pointing
straight up.

00:33:47.358 --> 00:33:52.195
And if you go down here,
you will find it looks like

00:33:52.195 --> 00:33:52.858
this.
 

00:33:52.858 --> 00:33:55.361
Now if you want to find the
field somewhere else,

00:33:55.361 --> 00:33:57.705
it's a lot of work,
because you don't have the

00:33:57.705 --> 00:34:00.259
symmetries, but I will tell you
what you get.

00:34:00.259 --> 00:34:05.935
You will get these lines that
look exactly like--I'm not

00:34:05.935 --> 00:34:11.510
showing you the other half,
but that looks the same.

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:16.780
Now that is supposed to remind
you again of a dipole.

00:34:16.780 --> 00:34:20.655
In fact, if you go to very,
very long distances,

00:34:20.655 --> 00:34:25.849
when z goes to infinity,
what does B look like?

00:34:25.849 --> 00:34:32.608
You go to the formula and let
z go to infinity,

00:34:32.608 --> 00:34:38.219
you will get--maybe I'll do it
again here.

00:34:38.219 --> 00:34:45.155
z goes to infinity,
B goes to

00:34:45.155 --> 00:34:51.429
μ_0
IΠR^(2),

00:34:51.429 --> 00:34:59.940
divided by 2Πz^(3).
 

00:34:59.940 --> 00:35:01.929
I'll tell you why I don't
cancel the pi's.

00:35:01.929 --> 00:35:06.474
I know you guys are dying to do
that, but ΠR^(2) times

00:35:06.474 --> 00:35:09.650
I is the dipole moment of
the loop.

00:35:09.650 --> 00:35:13.139
Remember, it's the area times
the current.

00:35:13.139 --> 00:35:17.250
So ignoring all the factors,
it looks like the dipole moment

00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:21.289
divided by the distance cubed,
that's exactly how the field

00:35:21.289 --> 00:35:23.518
went for an electric dipole.
 

00:35:23.518 --> 00:35:26.760
So the magnetic dipole and
electric dipole are,

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:27.960
again, similar.
 

00:35:27.960 --> 00:35:30.679
So they're similar in two ways.
 

00:35:30.679 --> 00:35:33.827
Just like the electric dipole
aligns with the electric field,

00:35:33.827 --> 00:35:36.610
the magnetic dipole aligns with
the magnetic field.

00:35:36.610 --> 00:35:38.360
That's the first thing.
 

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:42.030
The field of an electric dipole
has got these little circles

00:35:42.030 --> 00:35:45.391
going out and the field of a
magnetic dipole also looks

00:35:45.391 --> 00:35:46.760
exactly like that.
 

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:49.277
The only difference is,
if you go into an electric

00:35:49.277 --> 00:35:52.309
dipole, you'll find two guys,
and -, producing the field.

00:35:52.309 --> 00:35:54.557
If you go into a magnetic
dipole, you'll find nothing at

00:35:54.557 --> 00:35:55.090
the center.
 

00:35:55.090 --> 00:35:58.000
You'll just find a loop.
 

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:03.110
So nature gives us magnetic
dipoles, but not magnetic

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:04.289
monopoles.
 

00:36:04.289 --> 00:36:05.820
That doesn't mean they're not
there.

00:36:05.820 --> 00:36:07.409
People have been looking for
them.

00:36:07.409 --> 00:36:11.126
They've been spotted once,
but it's not been spotted

00:36:11.126 --> 00:36:11.710
again.
 

00:36:11.710 --> 00:36:13.702
It could be because they're
very rare, and they're very

00:36:13.702 --> 00:36:15.880
heavy and they're very hard to
measure, or maybe they're not

00:36:15.880 --> 00:36:16.250
there.
 

00:36:16.250 --> 00:36:17.139
We don't know.
 

00:36:17.139 --> 00:36:21.130
But we don't see them the way
we see electric charges to be

00:36:21.130 --> 00:36:22.369
sure they exist.
 

00:36:22.369 --> 00:36:29.494
Okay, now suppose I take one
coil and put under it a second

00:36:29.494 --> 00:36:37.358
coil and a third coil and I join
them all up and wrap them around

00:36:37.358 --> 00:36:44.527
some little cardboard tube,
you can imagine then these

00:36:44.527 --> 00:36:51.380
fields will all add up and
you'll get a field that looks

00:36:51.380 --> 00:36:53.000
like this.
 

00:36:53.000 --> 00:37:03.664
That looks exactly like a
magnetic field around a bar

00:37:03.664 --> 00:37:05.510
magnet.
 

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:06.230
Can you see that?
 

00:37:06.230 --> 00:37:07.730
You saw the field due to one.
 

00:37:07.730 --> 00:37:11.239
You can stack them up and then
you can compare the field.

00:37:11.239 --> 00:37:17.871
As far as a compass needle is
concerned, if you put it here or

00:37:17.871 --> 00:37:21.460
there, it behaves the same way.
 

00:37:21.460 --> 00:37:24.010
So now we have a question.
 

00:37:24.010 --> 00:37:27.768
Here is a magnetic effect due
to current carrying loop,

00:37:27.768 --> 00:37:29.230
or due to currents.
 

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:31.949
Here is a magnetic effect due
to no currents.

00:37:31.949 --> 00:37:34.960
Your magnet's not connected to
anything, so you have an option.

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:38.574
Either you can say that's a new
kind of magnetism produced by

00:37:38.574 --> 00:37:40.396
god knows what,
or you can say,

00:37:40.396 --> 00:37:43.052
"I believe that everything
is coming from electric

00:37:43.052 --> 00:37:45.018
currents,"
and the question is,

00:37:45.018 --> 00:37:48.909
where are the currents in this
guy?

00:37:48.909 --> 00:37:58.579
Do you know where the currents
are in a bar magnet?

00:37:58.579 --> 00:38:02.139
No?
 

00:38:02.139 --> 00:38:04.349
Okay, let me give you a hint.
 

00:38:04.349 --> 00:38:08.518
It comes from the atomic theory
of materials.

00:38:08.518 --> 00:38:09.920
Don't think of this as a lump
of something.

00:38:09.920 --> 00:38:10.590
Yes?
 

00:38:10.590 --> 00:38:11.900
Student:  The electrons.
 

00:38:11.900 --> 00:38:13.030
Prof: That's right.
 

00:38:13.030 --> 00:38:16.307
You know the atom has got
electrons going around,

00:38:16.307 --> 00:38:18.630
and every electron is a
current.

00:38:18.630 --> 00:38:25.284
Now you can ask,
let's put one electron here

00:38:25.284 --> 00:38:32.559
going like that,
then put another electron going

00:38:32.559 --> 00:38:39.989
like that, another electron
going like that.

00:38:39.989 --> 00:38:41.650
What do you think they all do
together?

00:38:41.650 --> 00:38:44.514
Suppose I've got nine electrons
in the plane of the blackboard

00:38:44.514 --> 00:38:45.969
all going around their atoms.
 

00:38:45.969 --> 00:38:48.512
You can see that in the region
between the atoms,

00:38:48.512 --> 00:38:50.260
they go in opposite directions.
 

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:52.139
This guy's going like that,
this guy's coming like this.

00:38:52.139 --> 00:38:54.610
They cancel.
 

00:38:54.610 --> 00:38:57.900
The only thing that doesn't
cancel is along the perimeter.

00:38:57.900 --> 00:39:02.590
Everybody--what are these guys
doing?

00:39:02.590 --> 00:39:03.230
Here we go.
 

00:39:03.230 --> 00:39:04.949
Sorry.
 

00:39:04.949 --> 00:39:09.420
Yes, they do this.
 

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:13.336
It's a physical fact that when
many orbits are put next to each

00:39:13.336 --> 00:39:16.876
other, they cancel on the
interior and give you something

00:39:16.876 --> 00:39:18.139
on the boundary.
 

00:39:18.139 --> 00:39:21.195
So even though each atom is a
very tiny loop,

00:39:21.195 --> 00:39:24.530
if you've got 10^(23) atoms,
they can look like a

00:39:24.530 --> 00:39:25.989
microscopic loop.
 

00:39:25.989 --> 00:39:28.418
Now that is just a two
dimensional loop,

00:39:28.418 --> 00:39:31.219
but you can take a solid,
a magnetic solid.

00:39:31.219 --> 00:39:34.010
It's go these little orbits
here.

00:39:34.010 --> 00:39:38.719
In every layer it's got orbits,
and each one is like a current.

00:39:38.719 --> 00:39:43.393
So magnetic material is like
having a sheet of current,

00:39:43.393 --> 00:39:47.809
and of course that will produce
a magnetic field.

00:39:47.809 --> 00:39:50.476
There are a lot of subtleties,
but this is roughly what

00:39:50.476 --> 00:39:50.969
happens.
 

00:39:50.969 --> 00:39:53.750
This is how you get magnetism.
 

00:39:53.750 --> 00:39:54.800
There are some questions.
 

00:39:54.800 --> 00:39:58.119
One of them is,
why isn't everything magnetic?

00:39:58.119 --> 00:40:00.059
Why not this guy?
 

00:40:00.059 --> 00:40:03.690
It's got electrons, right?
 

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:06.952
Why aren't they lined up,
and which way should they line

00:40:06.952 --> 00:40:07.250
up?
 

00:40:07.250 --> 00:40:09.789
Which way should the magnet
point?

00:40:09.789 --> 00:40:12.429
So the answer is,
many materials may contain

00:40:12.429 --> 00:40:15.989
equal number of electrons going
in opposite directions,

00:40:15.989 --> 00:40:18.170
so that some are going one way,
some are going the other way,

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:21.992
and for that reason,
each atom may cancel itself

00:40:21.992 --> 00:40:22.480
out.
 

00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:25.699
Another possibility is,
every atom may have one net

00:40:25.699 --> 00:40:29.050
uncancelled electrons,
but the plane of the orbit for

00:40:29.050 --> 00:40:30.789
each atom is different.
 

00:40:30.789 --> 00:40:33.155
Some are rotating in this
plane, some are rotating in that

00:40:33.155 --> 00:40:35.307
plane,
so there are little magnetic

00:40:35.307 --> 00:40:38.927
moment vectors pointing in
random directions and not lined

00:40:38.927 --> 00:40:39.309
up.
 

00:40:39.309 --> 00:40:42.460
And that happens because of
thermal agitation.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:44.559
Things like to jiggle when you
heat them.

00:40:44.559 --> 00:40:48.246
But when you cool them,
they can all line up and you

00:40:48.246 --> 00:40:51.210
suddenly find the material is
magnetic.

00:40:51.210 --> 00:40:55.032
So if you take a regular bar
magnet in your fridge and you

00:40:55.032 --> 00:40:58.452
put it on a hotplate for a
while, and you remove it,

00:40:58.452 --> 00:41:00.800
you'll find it's less magnetic.
 

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:03.735
So it's magnetic because you
caused these guys to jiggle

00:41:03.735 --> 00:41:04.110
more.
 

00:41:04.110 --> 00:41:06.699
And beyond a temperature called
curie temperature,

00:41:06.699 --> 00:41:10.007
which depends on the material,
the jiggling will be so intense

00:41:10.007 --> 00:41:13.085
that magnetism is destroyed,
not atom by atom,

00:41:13.085 --> 00:41:18.096
but because they're no longer
able to act together and produce

00:41:18.096 --> 00:41:20.150
a net magnetic moment.
 

00:41:20.150 --> 00:41:23.599
Then you can also take
materials in which every atom

00:41:23.599 --> 00:41:27.728
has an electron that's willing
to line up, but they don't know

00:41:27.728 --> 00:41:29.420
which way to line up.
 

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:31.429
They can line up in any way
they like,

00:41:31.429 --> 00:41:34.079
but then if you put them in a
strong magnetic field,

00:41:34.079 --> 00:41:36.817
then because every dipole likes
to line up with a magnetic

00:41:36.817 --> 00:41:39.128
field,
atomic moments line up with the

00:41:39.128 --> 00:41:40.099
magnetic field.
 

00:41:40.099 --> 00:41:43.007
And even if you take off the
magnetic field,

00:41:43.007 --> 00:41:44.969
the dipoles remain aligned.
 

00:41:44.969 --> 00:41:48.119
Do you know why they remain
aligned?

00:41:48.119 --> 00:41:51.514
Because they are producing
their own magnetic field which

00:41:51.514 --> 00:41:52.849
keeps them in place.
 

00:41:52.849 --> 00:41:55.670
That's called a self consistent
solution.

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:57.211
So the magnets,
if they all agree,

00:41:57.211 --> 00:41:58.952
"Hey,
let's line up,"

00:41:58.952 --> 00:42:01.329
can actually make it a stable
situation,

00:42:01.329 --> 00:42:05.143
because when they do line up,
they produce their own magnetic

00:42:05.143 --> 00:42:07.750
field which encourages them to
line up.

00:42:07.750 --> 00:42:10.090
These are all interesting
things in magnetism,

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:15.655
but the starting point always
is to find out how to take these

00:42:15.655 --> 00:42:19.670
microscopic moments and make
them line up.

00:42:19.670 --> 00:42:25.239
So now I'm going to do--so this
is at least an explanation of

00:42:25.239 --> 00:42:29.393
why bar magnets are magnetic,
because they are really

00:42:29.393 --> 00:42:33.121
circulating currents,
and it's no different from this

00:42:33.121 --> 00:42:33.860
current.
 

00:42:33.860 --> 00:42:42.012
Okay, now I'm going to find the
magnetic field for a very

00:42:42.012 --> 00:42:48.128
classic problem,
and that's the field of an

00:42:48.128 --> 00:42:50.750
infinite wire.
 

00:42:50.750 --> 00:42:55.313
So here is the infinite wire
and we want to find the field it

00:42:55.313 --> 00:42:56.150
produces.
 

00:42:56.150 --> 00:43:05.275
You take a point here,
and let's take some segment of

00:43:05.275 --> 00:43:08.610
length dx.
 

00:43:08.610 --> 00:43:15.398
And this is the separation
vector, and we want to find the

00:43:15.398 --> 00:43:19.449
field due to--dl is here.
 

00:43:19.449 --> 00:43:21.289
Now do the cross product.
 

00:43:21.289 --> 00:43:26.230
Turn screwdriver from dl
to R, it comes out of the

00:43:26.230 --> 00:43:27.250
blackboard.
 

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:31.215
So this little guy makes a
contribution that comes out of

00:43:31.215 --> 00:43:32.420
the blackboard.
 

00:43:32.420 --> 00:43:35.606
In fact, you can check that,
as you go along the line,

00:43:35.606 --> 00:43:39.335
everything acts in the same way
and makes a contribution coming

00:43:39.335 --> 00:43:40.900
out of the blackboard.
 

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:44.529
So what you can imagine is that
I just happened to slice it in

00:43:44.529 --> 00:43:48.039
this plane, but the real picture
is, the field lines will go

00:43:48.039 --> 00:43:49.230
around the wire.
 

00:43:49.230 --> 00:43:51.250
Right now they're coming out of
the blackboard.

00:43:51.250 --> 00:43:53.617
Down here they're going into
the blackboard,

00:43:53.617 --> 00:43:55.820
and they are orbiting around
the wire.

00:43:55.820 --> 00:43:59.804
If you look at the wire from
the end, then the current is

00:43:59.804 --> 00:44:01.300
coming towards you.
 

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:03.079
The field lines will look like
this.

00:44:03.079 --> 00:44:07.427
And what we're trying to
calculate is how strong is that

00:44:07.427 --> 00:44:08.059
field?
 

00:44:08.059 --> 00:44:12.876
So you go back to the famous
law, dB =

00:44:12.876 --> 00:44:18.349
μ_0I/4Π
times dl,

00:44:18.349 --> 00:44:28.150
which is just dx,
divided by x^(2) a^(2).

00:44:28.150 --> 00:44:34.280
Let's say the distance is
a.

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:38.199
Then you need the sine of the
angle between the separation

00:44:38.199 --> 00:44:42.760
vector of the segment,
and the sine of the angle,

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:48.989
sinθ, is a divided
by square root of x^(2)

00:44:48.989 --> 00:44:50.409
a^(2).
 

00:44:50.409 --> 00:44:58.592
Then the integral of dB
is the integral of all these

00:44:58.592 --> 00:44:59.579
guys.
 

00:44:59.579 --> 00:45:04.067
Now you can guess what the
final answer is going to look

00:45:04.067 --> 00:45:07.250
like, just from dimensional
analysis.

00:45:07.250 --> 00:45:09.309
dx is a length,
a is a length.

00:45:09.309 --> 00:45:11.340
There are two lengths on the
top.

00:45:11.340 --> 00:45:12.840
The bottom there are three
powers of length,

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.239
an x^(2) or a^(2)
from this one,

00:45:15.239 --> 00:45:16.969
and the square root of a length
squared,

00:45:16.969 --> 00:45:18.460
which is another length.
 

00:45:18.460 --> 00:45:19.409
You see that?
 

00:45:19.409 --> 00:45:22.039
Two powers of length at the
top, three in the bottom.

00:45:22.039 --> 00:45:24.914
The answer has to,
in the end, have dimensions of

00:45:24.914 --> 00:45:27.550
1 over length,
and the only length in town is

00:45:27.550 --> 00:45:27.909
a.
 

00:45:27.909 --> 00:45:32.590
So you know it's going to look
like μ_0I/a.

00:45:32.590 --> 00:45:35.690
But then it could be half of
a, or 10 times a.

00:45:35.690 --> 00:45:40.675
If you do that integral,
you'll find it's over

00:45:40.675 --> 00:45:42.449
2Πa.
 

00:45:42.449 --> 00:45:45.121
And I'm not doing the integral,
because we have seen this

00:45:45.121 --> 00:45:45.980
integral before.
 

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:48.639
dx over x^(2)
a^(2), to the 3/2.

00:45:48.639 --> 00:45:51.876
You make the tangent
substitution and then get secant

00:45:51.876 --> 00:45:53.309
this and secant that.
 

00:45:53.309 --> 00:45:55.990
So I don't want to do that
integral again,

00:45:55.990 --> 00:45:59.130
but the answer is
μ_0I/2a.

00:45:59.130 --> 00:46:03.789
so the magnetic field from an
infinite wire falls from a

00:46:03.789 --> 00:46:06.500
distance like 1 over a.
 

00:46:06.500 --> 00:46:08.268
Very much like the electric
problem.

00:46:08.268 --> 00:46:11.036
Even though single electric
charge produces a field that

00:46:11.036 --> 00:46:12.900
goes like 1 over r
squared,

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:15.782
if you remember,
infinite line produces a field

00:46:15.782 --> 00:46:17.849
that goes like 1 over r.
 

00:46:17.849 --> 00:46:20.061
Similarly, even though
elemental wire has a

00:46:20.061 --> 00:46:22.960
contribution that goes like 1
over distance squared,

00:46:22.960 --> 00:46:25.199
when integrated over an
infinite line,

00:46:25.199 --> 00:46:27.530
the final field goes like
a,

00:46:27.530 --> 00:46:33.317
1 over a,
where a is the distance

00:46:33.317 --> 00:46:36.840
from the axis of the wire.
 

00:46:36.840 --> 00:46:40.121
For a homework problem,
I want you to notice that in

00:46:40.121 --> 00:46:42.440
this integral from - to
infinity,

00:46:42.440 --> 00:46:47.170
the segment for the axis,
the segment for the - axis make

00:46:47.170 --> 00:46:49.030
equal contributions.
 

00:46:49.030 --> 00:46:51.440
In other words,
if you take this to be origin,

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:54.762
that segment and that segment
contribute equally to the field

00:46:54.762 --> 00:46:57.804
at any point,
because it's an even function

00:46:57.804 --> 00:46:58.768
of x.
 

00:46:58.768 --> 00:47:02.050
You will find it useful when
you do the problem set.

00:47:02.050 --> 00:47:06.291
Okay, so here is an interesting
result, μ_0

00:47:06.291 --> 00:47:07.389
I/2Πa.
 

00:47:07.389 --> 00:47:10.199
Now that's going to explain a
few things.

00:47:10.199 --> 00:47:14.141
So here is a wire and I told
you long back when we started

00:47:14.141 --> 00:47:16.599
magnetism,
I said, if you put a test

00:47:16.599 --> 00:47:18.909
charge here and it moves like
this,

00:47:18.909 --> 00:47:22.460
it's attracted to the wire.
 

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:26.070
Now we can understand their
attraction.

00:47:26.070 --> 00:47:29.452
We understand the attraction as
follows - look at the thing from

00:47:29.452 --> 00:47:31.677
end on,
the current is coming--what do

00:47:31.677 --> 00:47:34.768
you think the direction of the
magnetic field here is?

00:47:34.768 --> 00:47:37.934
Again, you put your thumbs
around this one,

00:47:37.934 --> 00:47:41.099
it's curling,
therefore it's going into the

00:47:41.099 --> 00:47:45.469
blackboard here and coming out
of the blackboard here.

00:47:45.469 --> 00:47:50.313
That is the azimuthal magnetic
field seen from the plane of the

00:47:50.313 --> 00:47:51.329
blackboard.
 

00:47:51.329 --> 00:47:54.400
You've got this guy going to
velocity v here.

00:47:54.400 --> 00:47:58.556
Take the cross product of
v with somebody going

00:47:58.556 --> 00:48:02.242
into the blackboard,
you'll find you get a force

00:48:02.242 --> 00:48:03.889
towards the wire.
 

00:48:03.889 --> 00:48:06.867
That's why the charged particle
going along the current is

00:48:06.867 --> 00:48:09.739
attracted to the current,
if it's positively charged.

00:48:09.739 --> 00:48:13.266
If it's going in the opposite
direction, if you reverse the

00:48:13.266 --> 00:48:15.760
velocity, you will get the
opposite force,

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:18.010
so it will go away from the
wire.

00:48:18.010 --> 00:48:20.922
Finally, I want to mention the
experiment that people did

00:48:20.922 --> 00:48:23.990
before any of this which is to
notice that if you've got two

00:48:23.990 --> 00:48:25.599
currents,
l_1 and

00:48:25.599 --> 00:48:28.831
l_2,
they attract each other if they

00:48:28.831 --> 00:48:32.980
are parallel and they repel if
they're anti-parallel.

00:48:32.980 --> 00:48:36.041
So if you went and asked
yourself, "How am I going

00:48:36.041 --> 00:48:39.215
to find the force that's
attractive when they're parallel

00:48:39.215 --> 00:48:41.199
or they're anti-parallel?"
 

00:48:41.199 --> 00:48:43.452
you can think of all kinds of
simple rules,

00:48:43.452 --> 00:48:46.780
maybe involving this current
vector and that current vector.

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:50.603
But the correct answer is a
pretty complicated series of

00:48:50.603 --> 00:48:53.940
cross products on why these two
wires attract.

00:48:53.940 --> 00:48:56.010
Let me tell you why they
attract.

00:48:56.010 --> 00:48:57.809
I think you can see yourself.
 

00:48:57.809 --> 00:49:01.389
Take the force on this guy due
to I_1.

00:49:01.389 --> 00:49:06.364
It produces a field that looks
like this there and looks like

00:49:06.364 --> 00:49:07.360
that here.
 

00:49:07.360 --> 00:49:12.025
So just like the single charge
here, this experiences a force

00:49:12.025 --> 00:49:15.369
towards the other wire,
every part of it.

00:49:15.369 --> 00:49:20.059
So the force that current 2
feels due to current 1 is

00:49:20.059 --> 00:49:24.389
μ_0I
_1/2Πa,

00:49:24.389 --> 00:49:26.489
where a is the distance between
them.

00:49:26.489 --> 00:49:30.768
That is my B.
 

00:49:30.768 --> 00:49:32.960
I, and that's my
l.

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:35.340
If l_2
is the length of this wire.

00:49:35.340 --> 00:49:39.302
I'm just using the formula
BIl I told you

00:49:39.302 --> 00:49:39.889
about.
 

00:49:39.889 --> 00:49:42.581
So the B is the B
due to the first wire,

00:49:42.581 --> 00:49:45.525
I is the current of the
second wire, l is the

00:49:45.525 --> 00:49:47.050
length of the second wire.
 

00:49:47.050 --> 00:49:49.454
So if you took an infinite
second wire, you're going to get

00:49:49.454 --> 00:49:51.815
nonsense, because you'll get
infinity as the force between

00:49:51.815 --> 00:49:52.768
two infinite wires.
 

00:49:52.768 --> 00:49:55.380
So it's more common to take the
force.

00:49:55.380 --> 00:49:58.539
Let me drop the arrow on this,
because I'm looking at the

00:49:58.539 --> 00:50:00.119
magnitude per unit length.
 

00:50:00.119 --> 00:50:05.463
Then it is just this,
μ_0I

00:50:05.463 --> 00:50:12.110
_1I_2
over 2Πa.

00:50:12.110 --> 00:50:13.677
And the current,
you know, is measured in

00:50:13.677 --> 00:50:16.072
amperes,
which means if you took 1

00:50:16.072 --> 00:50:19.840
ampere in this wire and 1 ampere
in that wire,

00:50:19.840 --> 00:50:23.096
and they were 1 meter apart,
the force between them will be

00:50:23.096 --> 00:50:27.764
μ_0/2Π,
which will be 2 times 10^(-7)

00:50:27.764 --> 00:50:30.190
newtons per unit length.
 

00:50:30.190 --> 00:50:32.204
In other words,
if you're all holding this wire

00:50:32.204 --> 00:50:34.896
from running off to that wire,
and you are given 1 meter of

00:50:34.896 --> 00:50:39.148
the wire to take care of,
you will have to exert that

00:50:39.148 --> 00:50:39.940
force.
 

00:50:39.940 --> 00:50:43.675
So attraction between wires in
the end has an explanation,

00:50:43.675 --> 00:50:45.510
but it's very complicated.
 

00:50:45.510 --> 00:50:49.500
It does not simply involve the
two current directions.

00:50:49.500 --> 00:50:51.853
The first current,
through a series of cross

00:50:51.853 --> 00:50:54.226
products,
produces a magnetic field

00:50:54.226 --> 00:50:57.835
perpendicular to this wire,
and another cross product of

00:50:57.835 --> 00:51:01.413
that perpendicular field and the
current here gives you another

00:51:01.413 --> 00:51:03.780
vector which is the attraction
vector.

00:51:03.780 --> 00:51:05.840
So the force of attraction,
whereas force of attraction

00:51:05.840 --> 00:51:07.597
between two charges is simply
q_1

00:51:07.597 --> 00:51:09.429
q_2 over r
squared,

00:51:09.429 --> 00:51:11.289
force of attraction between two
wires,

00:51:11.289 --> 00:51:13.159
even though it has a simple
formula,

00:51:13.159 --> 00:51:16.449
comes in the end from a whole
bunch of cross products.

00:51:16.449 --> 00:51:28.050
That's what you have to know.
 

00:51:28.050 --> 00:51:45.166
All right, so now I'm going to
do a very basic result called

00:51:45.166 --> 00:51:49.518
Ampere's law.
 

00:51:49.518 --> 00:51:53.900
Ampere's law says the following
- look at the current coming

00:51:53.900 --> 00:51:54.940
towards you.
 

00:51:54.940 --> 00:52:00.469
The field lines go like this.
 

00:52:00.469 --> 00:52:04.289
Let me call that angle Φ.
 

00:52:04.289 --> 00:52:08.655
Then the magnetic field is a
unit vector in the Φ

00:52:08.655 --> 00:52:12.601
direction times
μ_0I divided

00:52:12.601 --> 00:52:16.710
by 2Πr,
where r is the distance.

00:52:16.710 --> 00:52:18.639
This is the wire, okay?
 

00:52:18.639 --> 00:52:21.650
And I am looking at various
circles.

00:52:21.650 --> 00:52:25.639
This is the circle of radius
r. Here is what B

00:52:25.639 --> 00:52:26.518
looks like.
 

00:52:26.518 --> 00:52:30.235
So B is circulating
around the wire,

00:52:30.235 --> 00:52:32.980
very different from E.
 

00:52:32.980 --> 00:52:37.989
E emanates from charges,
but has no circulation.

00:52:37.989 --> 00:52:41.389
Its line integral on a closed
loop is 0, electrostatically.

00:52:41.389 --> 00:52:43.420
The magnetic field is just the
opposite.

00:52:43.420 --> 00:52:46.427
It's always going around in
circles and therefore has a line

00:52:46.427 --> 00:52:48.389
integral,
and I will mention later on

00:52:48.389 --> 00:52:51.811
that it has no surface integral,
because Bs don't start

00:52:51.811 --> 00:52:52.880
and end anywhere.
 

00:52:52.880 --> 00:52:55.588
The lines of B,
therefore if you took any

00:52:55.588 --> 00:52:58.182
surface, whatever line comes in
has to go out,

00:52:58.182 --> 00:52:59.739
because it cannot stop.
 

00:52:59.739 --> 00:53:03.494
I'll come to that in a minute,
but let's look at the line

00:53:03.494 --> 00:53:06.110
integral of B around a
circle.

00:53:06.110 --> 00:53:11.800
B⋅dr
around a circle.

00:53:11.800 --> 00:53:17.500
So on a circle,
take a section of a circle.

00:53:17.500 --> 00:53:22.039
So here is my portion of a
circle.

00:53:22.039 --> 00:53:26.463
dR =
