00:55:00.038 --> 00:55:02.860
loop,
penetrated by a current,

00:55:02.860 --> 00:55:08.527
= μ_0 times
the current coming out of that

00:55:08.527 --> 00:55:09.550
surface.
 

00:55:09.550 --> 00:55:12.030
Independent of the radius of
the circle.

00:55:12.030 --> 00:55:14.885
You can take a small circle,
you can take a big circle,

00:55:14.885 --> 00:55:16.630
you always get the same answer.
 

00:55:16.630 --> 00:55:19.313
Because if you take a big
circle, you've got a big

00:55:19.313 --> 00:55:21.449
circumference growing like
r,

00:55:21.449 --> 00:55:25.579
but the field goes like 1 over
r and the effects cancel.

00:55:25.579 --> 00:55:30.659
This remind you of something
you've seen before?

00:55:30.659 --> 00:55:31.489
Which one?
 

00:55:31.489 --> 00:55:32.820
Student:  The plane.
 

00:55:32.820 --> 00:55:35.719
Prof: No,
where these things cancel.

00:55:35.719 --> 00:55:36.550
Pardon me?
 

00:55:36.550 --> 00:55:42.530
Student:  Gauss's law
_______________.

00:55:42.530 --> 00:55:44.079
Prof: Like Gauss's law,
you mean?

00:55:44.079 --> 00:55:44.829
Student:  Yes.
 

00:55:44.829 --> 00:55:45.856
Prof: Yes,
Gauss's law,

00:55:45.856 --> 00:55:48.867
where you took a single charge,
the surface integral of E

00:55:48.867 --> 00:55:51.969
was independent of the size
of the sphere,

00:55:51.969 --> 00:55:54.980
because the field went like 1
over r^(2).

00:55:54.980 --> 00:55:57.097
Area of the sphere went like
r^(2),

00:55:57.097 --> 00:55:59.989
and surface integral just said
it's equal to the q

00:55:59.989 --> 00:56:00.920
that's inside.
 

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:03.769
Then of course we found it's
true, even if the shape is not

00:56:03.769 --> 00:56:04.360
spherical.
 

00:56:04.360 --> 00:56:07.478
Again, we find here,
first you take a circle and you

00:56:07.478 --> 00:56:11.210
find the answer is independent
of the radius of the circle.

00:56:11.210 --> 00:56:15.648
Then I'm going to show you that
the answer is independent,

00:56:15.648 --> 00:56:18.139
even of the shape of the loop.
 

00:56:18.139 --> 00:56:22.110
So let the current be here.
 

00:56:22.110 --> 00:56:28.050
So take a loop like that.
 

00:56:28.050 --> 00:56:35.900
So take a portion of that loop,
this portion here.

00:56:35.900 --> 00:56:41.849
It's got a radial part and a
tangential part.

00:56:41.849 --> 00:56:46.987
So you can see the dr of
the loop is dr times

00:56:46.987 --> 00:56:51.152
e_r
rdΦ times

00:56:51.152 --> 00:56:54.429
e_
Φ.

00:56:54.429 --> 00:56:56.018
Let me blow this up for you if
you like.

00:56:56.018 --> 00:57:01.092
So that is that segment there,
dr, and that's got an

00:57:01.092 --> 00:57:03.980
angular part and a radial part.
 

00:57:03.980 --> 00:57:08.059
The radial part is length
dr, the angular part is

00:57:08.059 --> 00:57:10.360
length rdΦ.
 

00:57:10.360 --> 00:57:13.659
So integrating along that
curve, which I can approximate

00:57:13.659 --> 00:57:16.931
by a straight line,
I can break up that elemental

00:57:16.931 --> 00:57:20.500
vector dr into the tiny portion
in the angular one,

00:57:20.500 --> 00:57:22.340
tiny portion in the radial one.
 

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:27.534
But B =
μ_0I/2Πr

00:57:27.534 --> 00:57:32.268
times e_
Φ.

00:57:32.268 --> 00:57:35.050
So when you take
B⋅dr,

00:57:35.050 --> 00:57:36.188
e_r
⋅

00:57:36.188 --> 00:57:37.360
e_Φ is
0,

00:57:37.360 --> 00:57:39.559
because they are perpendicular
vectors.

00:57:39.559 --> 00:57:46.846
All you get then is
B⋅dr

00:57:46.846 --> 00:57:53.538
will be μ_0I
over 2Π

00:57:53.538 --> 00:57:56.809
dΦ.
 

00:57:56.809 --> 00:58:01.827
So the line integral of B
receives the contribution

00:58:01.827 --> 00:58:07.373
equal to simply the angle of the
two rays that bound this little

00:58:07.373 --> 00:58:08.429
segment.
 

00:58:08.429 --> 00:58:10.889
Then you can see if you go
around the whole loop,

00:58:10.889 --> 00:58:14.346
you will just add up all the
dΦ's and you

00:58:14.346 --> 00:58:16.550
will get 2Π and you
will get

00:58:16.550 --> 00:58:18.280
μ_0I.
 

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:22.025
So the answer is true,
even if it is not a circle,

00:58:22.025 --> 00:58:25.846
as long as it is a closed loop,
enclosing the wire,

00:58:25.846 --> 00:58:29.210
the answer is equal to current
enclosed.

00:58:29.210 --> 00:58:41.110
What if you took a loop here
and the current's actually here?

00:58:41.110 --> 00:58:44.731
There's no current going out of
this guy, so we'd better get 0

00:58:44.731 --> 00:58:46.809
for that and we want to know
why.

00:58:46.809 --> 00:58:49.469
You'll get 0 because if you do
the same formula,

00:58:49.469 --> 00:58:50.909
it will give you integral of
dΦ,

00:58:50.909 --> 00:58:54.780
but notice if you go round here
and come back all the way here,

00:58:54.780 --> 00:58:56.190
the change in Φ is 0.
 

00:58:56.190 --> 00:58:58.268
Can you see that?
 

00:58:58.268 --> 00:59:02.163
In any loop bounded by some
lines, the range of Φ

00:59:02.163 --> 00:59:04.710
as you follow it goes back to
0.

00:59:04.710 --> 00:59:08.969
Whereas if you encircle the
origin, then Φ

00:59:08.969 --> 00:59:10.768
changes by 2Π.
 

00:59:10.768 --> 00:59:13.871
So if you take a point here and
you go around in a loop,

00:59:13.871 --> 00:59:15.789
you come back to the same
Φ.

00:59:15.789 --> 00:59:18.393
If you take a point here and
you go around,

00:59:18.393 --> 00:59:19.820
phi goes up by 2Π.
 

00:59:19.820 --> 00:59:23.204
That's why a loop not enclosing
a current will get 0

00:59:23.204 --> 00:59:24.199
contribution.
 

00:59:24.199 --> 00:59:28.639
A loop enclosing a current will
get μ_0I.

00:59:28.639 --> 00:59:32.835
And finally,
by superposition,

00:59:32.835 --> 00:59:40.360
if you've got many,
many wires coming out of this.

00:59:40.360 --> 00:59:41.869
Some are going in,
some are coming out,

00:59:41.869 --> 00:59:43.980
some are going in,
some are coming out,

00:59:43.980 --> 00:59:49.646
then integral of
B⋅dr =

00:59:49.646 --> 00:59:55.550
μ_0 times sum of
all the currents,

00:59:55.550 --> 01:00:16.130
I_j penetrates
the surface bounded by the loop.

01:00:16.130 --> 01:00:19.250
That's because B is made
up of B due to this guy,

01:00:19.250 --> 01:00:22.300
that guy, that guy,
but the integral of the total

01:00:22.300 --> 01:00:24.780
B is the individual
integrals.

01:00:24.780 --> 01:00:27.119
Each one gives you its own
current.

01:00:27.119 --> 01:00:31.030
So superposition is a great and
powerful result.

01:00:31.030 --> 01:00:33.652
If you can do anything for one
charge or one current,

01:00:33.652 --> 01:00:35.719
you're able to add everything
together.

01:00:35.719 --> 01:00:50.960
So this is called the law of
Ampere.

01:00:50.960 --> 01:00:57.094
Now I might as well tell you,
the surface integral of

01:00:57.094 --> 01:01:02.639
B on any closed surface
is actually 0.

01:01:02.639 --> 01:01:07.286
Because if you took electric
charges, they've got lines

01:01:07.286 --> 01:01:09.869
coming out like this,
right?

01:01:09.869 --> 01:01:13.458
And if you took a surface,
you get some contribution from

01:01:13.458 --> 01:01:17.239
the dot product of the field
vector with the area vector.

01:01:17.239 --> 01:01:19.920
Magnetic lines never end
anywhere.

01:01:19.920 --> 01:01:21.829
They always close.
 

01:01:21.829 --> 01:01:26.389
So take whatever surface you
want, any line that enters it

01:01:26.389 --> 01:01:30.630
will also leave it,
because there's nowhere to end.

01:01:30.630 --> 01:01:34.244
Had there been magnetic
charges, magnetic monopoles,

01:01:34.244 --> 01:01:38.355
lines will either come out of
the monopole or collapse into

01:01:38.355 --> 01:01:39.559
the monopole.
 

01:01:39.559 --> 01:01:42.688
Then the surface integral of
B will count the magnetic

01:01:42.688 --> 01:01:43.210
charges.
 

01:01:43.210 --> 01:01:44.679
But we have not found any.
 

01:01:44.679 --> 01:01:46.994
So as of now,
the surface integral of

01:01:46.994 --> 01:01:49.757
B is 0,
the line integral of B

01:01:49.757 --> 01:01:52.329
is the current trapped by that
loop.

01:01:52.329 --> 01:01:52.860
Do you understand?
 

01:01:52.860 --> 01:01:57.784
You take that loop and you draw
a plane with that loop as a

01:01:57.784 --> 01:01:58.719
boundary.
 

01:01:58.719 --> 01:02:02.476
Then any current coming out of
that is going to be equal to the

01:02:02.476 --> 01:02:04.719
line integral up to this factor
mu.

01:02:04.719 --> 01:02:07.090
For the electric field,
just for comparison,

01:02:07.090 --> 01:02:12.027
the line integral of the
electric field is 0 and the

01:02:12.027 --> 01:02:17.351
surface integral of the electric
field = the charge over

01:02:17.351 --> 01:02:19.869
ε_0.
 

01:02:19.869 --> 01:02:21.829
So here is this one integral.
 

01:02:21.829 --> 01:02:25.485
Let me write it here,
B⋅dr

01:02:25.485 --> 01:02:29.500
= μ_0 times all the
currents crossing it.

01:02:29.500 --> 01:02:34.860
So it's very useful for you to
write these 4 mathematical

01:02:34.860 --> 01:02:36.010
equations.
 

01:02:36.010 --> 01:02:47.619
These are called the integral
form of the Maxwell equations,

01:02:47.619 --> 01:02:50.851
namely, it's the relation
between electric and magnetic

01:02:50.851 --> 01:02:54.143
fields written in terms of the
integrals of electric and

01:02:54.143 --> 01:02:55.340
magnetic fields.
 

01:02:55.340 --> 01:02:57.208
There's something called the
differential form of the

01:02:57.208 --> 01:02:58.610
magnetic field which is more
useful,

01:02:58.610 --> 01:03:06.561
which requires more mathematics
than we have done in this

01:03:06.561 --> 01:03:07.840
course.
 

01:03:07.840 --> 01:03:11.514
But this is all for the case of
electrostatics and

01:03:11.514 --> 01:03:14.440
magnetostatics,
very, very important.

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:17.059
All the currents have to be
constant;

01:03:17.059 --> 01:03:19.260
all the charges have to be
fixed.

01:03:19.260 --> 01:03:25.059
Only then is this true.
 

01:03:25.059 --> 01:03:28.103
It turns out this is all you
really need to determine

01:03:28.103 --> 01:03:29.920
electric and magnetic fields.
 

01:03:29.920 --> 01:03:32.952
Suppose someone comes to you
and says, "I'm going to

01:03:32.952 --> 01:03:34.469
give you all the currents.
 

01:03:34.469 --> 01:03:37.139
I'm going to give you all the
charges.

01:03:37.139 --> 01:03:39.619
Can you find E and
B?"

01:03:39.619 --> 01:03:41.230
It's a mathematical problem.
 

01:03:41.230 --> 01:03:44.512
The mathematical statement is
you know the line integral of

01:03:44.512 --> 01:03:47.967
either field around any loop and
you know the surface integral

01:03:47.967 --> 01:03:49.268
around any surface.
 

01:03:49.268 --> 01:03:52.469
It turns out that's all you
need.

01:03:52.469 --> 01:03:55.422
The line and surface integrals
are known for every possible

01:03:55.422 --> 01:03:58.630
loop and every possible surface,
then the solution is unique.

01:03:58.630 --> 01:04:03.447
That's why this is all you
really need to do any problem in

01:04:03.447 --> 01:04:04.860
magnetostatics.
 

01:04:04.860 --> 01:04:07.132
Because you might think,
maybe this guy's going to write

01:04:07.132 --> 01:04:08.000
two more equations.
 

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:11.179
I'm saying mathematically,
this is complete.

01:04:11.179 --> 01:04:13.860
On the other hand,
if I stopped at one of them,

01:04:13.860 --> 01:04:16.820
except for the electric field,
if all I told you was this one,

01:04:16.820 --> 01:04:23.219
then mathematically it's not
enough to solve the problem.

01:04:23.219 --> 01:04:29.313
Okay, so I'm going to use
Ampere's law the way I used

01:04:29.313 --> 01:04:35.289
Gauss's law to show you some
simple applications.

01:04:35.289 --> 01:04:39.737
Suppose someone gives you an
infinite wire and says,

01:04:39.737 --> 01:04:43.139
"Find the field around
it."

01:04:43.139 --> 01:04:46.744
Now you can do that nasty
integral which I did on the top

01:04:46.744 --> 01:04:49.768
right corner,
but now we don't have to do it.

01:04:49.768 --> 01:04:55.079
Because you will argue by
symmetry that the field here

01:04:55.079 --> 01:05:00.989
cannot be pointing to the left
or pointing to the right,

01:05:00.989 --> 01:05:03.902
should lie in the plane,
because there's no reason to

01:05:03.902 --> 01:05:05.469
bias one way or the other.
 

01:05:05.469 --> 01:05:08.639
And in the plane perpendicular
to it, the field should be

01:05:08.639 --> 01:05:12.094
invariant when you rotate the
wire, because the wire looks the

01:05:12.094 --> 01:05:13.679
same when you rotate it.
 

01:05:13.679 --> 01:05:16.681
So the only possible things I
can think of are,

01:05:16.681 --> 01:05:20.271
the field can look like this,
or the field can look like

01:05:20.271 --> 01:05:20.860
this.
 

01:05:20.860 --> 01:05:24.601
They both have the property
that when you rotate the wire,

01:05:24.601 --> 01:05:25.980
they look the same.
 

01:05:25.980 --> 01:05:28.710
But you can rule this one out.
 

01:05:28.710 --> 01:05:31.867
One way to rule it out is to
say that if all the magnetic

01:05:31.867 --> 01:05:35.137
field lines end on the wire,
there must be magnetic charges

01:05:35.137 --> 01:05:36.659
and we don't have them.
 

01:05:36.659 --> 01:05:39.099
Another way which is more
subtle is to say,

01:05:39.099 --> 01:05:42.750
if this was the field
configuration for this current,

01:05:42.750 --> 01:05:46.862
if I reverse the current,
everything should reverse and

01:05:46.862 --> 01:05:49.530
the lines should go outwards
now.

01:05:49.530 --> 01:05:52.081
On the other hand,
if I took this infinite wire

01:05:52.081 --> 01:05:54.690
and I rotated it like that
around this axis,

01:05:54.690 --> 01:05:56.789
the current will point the
other way,

01:05:56.789 --> 01:06:00.690
but the field lines would still
keep going radially in.

01:06:00.690 --> 01:06:04.235
That means if I took that
current and I flipped it around,

01:06:04.235 --> 01:06:07.780
the field lines still go the
center, but I has become - I,

01:06:07.780 --> 01:06:09.710
so that rules this one out.
 

01:06:09.710 --> 01:06:13.409
But you can easily satisfy
yourself with this configuration

01:06:13.409 --> 01:06:16.920
of circling things will satisfy
all the requirements.

01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:20.760
So I know the field is
azimuthal, goes around the wire.

01:06:20.760 --> 01:06:23.472
I know it depends only on the
distance from the wire and not

01:06:23.472 --> 01:06:26.737
where I am in the circle,
therefore I look at the wire

01:06:26.737 --> 01:06:30.762
end on and I know that there's a
field here in the angular

01:06:30.762 --> 01:06:31.679
direction.
 

01:06:31.679 --> 01:06:35.923
I also know the line integral
of B⋅dr

01:06:35.923 --> 01:06:38.340
= μ_0I.
 

01:06:38.340 --> 01:06:39.969
This is like Gauss's law.
 

01:06:39.969 --> 01:06:42.630
You cannot find from it
B separately,

01:06:42.630 --> 01:06:45.978
except in the lucky case where
B⋅dr

01:06:45.978 --> 01:06:48.610
is a constant over the
entire circle,

01:06:48.610 --> 01:06:52.177
which it is in this case,
because it's simply B

01:06:52.177 --> 01:06:53.659
times 2Πr.
 

01:06:53.659 --> 01:06:56.438
If B is azimuthal,
which I've argued for,

01:06:56.438 --> 01:06:59.394
the line integral is B
times 2Πr =

01:06:59.394 --> 01:07:01.110
μ_0I.
 

01:07:01.110 --> 01:07:08.018
That means B = μ_0
I/2Πr.

01:07:08.018 --> 01:07:11.414
So what I'm telling you is just
like Gauss's law,

01:07:11.414 --> 01:07:13.820
will only give you one
equation.

01:07:13.820 --> 01:07:18.996
If you told me to find the
field due to an arbitrary

01:07:18.996 --> 01:07:23.362
distribution of currents,
I can still write this true

01:07:23.362 --> 01:07:26.507
statement,
but I cannot deduce from it the

01:07:26.507 --> 01:07:28.018
value of B.
 

01:07:28.018 --> 01:07:30.170
But if it's due to this
infinite wire and you've got

01:07:30.170 --> 01:07:32.574
enough symmetries and the only
thing you don't know is the

01:07:32.574 --> 01:07:34.599
magnitude of B as you
vary r,

01:07:34.599 --> 01:07:36.429
then on a contour of fixed
r,

01:07:36.429 --> 01:07:37.699
there's only one unknown,
which is,

01:07:37.699 --> 01:07:40.648
how big is B as a
function of r in the

01:07:40.648 --> 01:07:41.920
azimuthal direction.
 

01:07:41.920 --> 01:07:46.530
Then the one number you get
from this one equation.

01:07:46.530 --> 01:07:52.559
Now here's another variation of
that problem.

01:07:52.559 --> 01:07:56.969
They all have analogs in
electrostatics.

01:07:56.969 --> 01:08:03.583
Imagine that I have a solid
cable carrying current I,

01:08:03.583 --> 01:08:07.059
coming out of the blackboard.
 

01:08:07.059 --> 01:08:11.780
And let's say this cable has
radius R.

01:08:11.780 --> 01:08:17.310
Then I want the magnetic field
here.

01:08:17.310 --> 01:08:20.091
Now the real problem is much
more difficult than before,

01:08:20.091 --> 01:08:23.380
because there you had a single
line, you could do the integral.

01:08:23.380 --> 01:08:25.538
If you have a blob,
a cylindrical blob,

01:08:25.538 --> 01:08:28.836
you do all the dl cross
r's for everything is

01:08:28.836 --> 01:08:30.939
going to be very,
very difficult.

01:08:30.939 --> 01:08:35.220
But now we're going to argue by
symmetry that this one should

01:08:35.220 --> 01:08:39.359
also have necessarily fields
that go around in circles,

01:08:39.359 --> 01:08:42.220
with a uniform strength on a
circle of given radius.

01:08:42.220 --> 01:08:46.154
Then you conclude then that
2Πr times B =

01:08:46.154 --> 01:08:48.020
μ_0I.
 

01:08:48.020 --> 01:08:54.158
Therefore B =
μ_0I divided

01:08:54.158 --> 01:08:59.176
by 2Πr,
which is exactly the field you

01:08:59.176 --> 01:09:03.960
would get from a point wire
carrying all the current.

01:09:03.960 --> 01:09:06.439
Again, this should remind you
of Gauss's law,

01:09:06.439 --> 01:09:10.101
but if you have a ball of
charge, the field due to it

01:09:10.101 --> 01:09:14.538
looks like the field of a point
charge sitting at its center.

01:09:14.538 --> 01:09:17.328
Likewise the field of a uniform
distribution,

01:09:17.328 --> 01:09:19.779
a tube of current coming
towards you,

01:09:19.779 --> 01:09:23.729
outside this tube looks like
it's all coming from the center,

01:09:23.729 --> 01:09:27.228
because that's what it will
look like if the entire current

01:09:27.228 --> 01:09:29.279
were concentrated on the center.
 

01:09:29.279 --> 01:09:31.430
But you will see the difference
now.

01:09:31.430 --> 01:09:36.270
If you go inside this and ask,
what's the magnetic field on a

01:09:36.270 --> 01:09:40.149
circle lying inside this,
then again you can say

01:09:40.149 --> 01:09:44.270
2Πr times B =
μ_0 times the

01:09:44.270 --> 01:09:47.289
current that's enclosed by that
loop,

01:09:47.289 --> 01:09:49.390
not the entire current.
 

01:09:49.390 --> 01:09:54.217
And I think by now you guys
should know, that will be this

01:09:54.217 --> 01:09:56.930
fraction of the total current.
 

01:09:56.930 --> 01:10:00.036
Or if you want to see the
details, you can put a pi there

01:10:00.036 --> 01:10:01.590
and you can put a pi here.
 

01:10:01.590 --> 01:10:04.003
I/ΠR^(2) is
the current density and

01:10:04.003 --> 01:10:06.038
ΠR^(2) is the area of
this guy.

01:10:06.038 --> 01:10:09.246
But by now you guys should know
that things scale like distance

01:10:09.246 --> 01:10:11.159
squared if you're looking at
areas.

01:10:11.159 --> 01:10:12.470
So what does that tell me now?
 

01:10:12.470 --> 01:10:15.641
It's
μ_0Ir^(2)

01:10:15.641 --> 01:10:17.948
over big R^(2).
 

01:10:17.948 --> 01:10:21.479
So for B,
it looks like

01:10:21.479 --> 01:10:28.538
μ_0Ir
divided by 2ΠR^(2),

01:10:28.538 --> 01:10:31.270
with r less than or
equal to R.

01:10:31.270 --> 01:10:34.530
And this is the formula for
r bigger than or equal to

01:10:34.530 --> 01:10:35.140
R.
 

01:10:35.140 --> 01:10:41.630
And you can test the formula
when little r = R.

01:10:41.630 --> 01:10:42.520
That's correct.
 

01:10:42.520 --> 01:10:45.970
Little r = R, they agree.
 

01:10:45.970 --> 01:10:51.662
Therefore the magnetic field as
a function of r grows

01:10:51.662 --> 01:10:56.680
inside the cylinder and then
decays as 1/r.

01:10:56.680 --> 01:10:59.537
All this should be familiar to
you if you still remember

01:10:59.537 --> 01:11:01.408
similar problems from Gauss's
law.

01:11:01.408 --> 01:11:03.988
If you've got a ball of charge,
the electric charge grows

01:11:03.988 --> 01:11:05.828
linearly when you're inside the
ball,

01:11:05.828 --> 01:11:08.320
because as you grow,
you're enclosing more and more

01:11:08.320 --> 01:11:10.103
charge,
which is growing like

01:11:10.103 --> 01:11:12.554
r^(3),
but the sphere is growing like

01:11:12.554 --> 01:11:13.270
r^(2).
 

01:11:13.270 --> 01:11:16.198
So it grows like r,
but once you cross the sphere,

01:11:16.198 --> 01:11:18.189
you go to bigger and bigger
spheres,

01:11:18.189 --> 01:11:20.430
you're not enclosing more
charge, but the sphere for

01:11:20.430 --> 01:11:23.689
Gauss's law is getting bigger,
so it falls like 1/r^(2).

01:11:23.689 --> 01:11:27.291
Similarly here,
it falls like 1/r when

01:11:27.291 --> 01:11:31.466
you're outside the cylinder,
and grows linearly with

01:11:31.466 --> 01:11:35.149
r when you're inside the
cylinder.

